			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I actually don't think that they should even consider adding an extra AA to have pets zone with you or not. This should be done by default without any AA ability at all. That's what I'd like to see. 
<br />

<br />
In an ideal MMORPG world, the world would be fluent but the hardware and fundamental core design of the game is just isn't there to support that kind of a fluent game world where zoning between different areas is seamless and things don't disappear when moving from one location to another when a short loading period is required in between.
<br />

<br />
We know that the idea of zones was created to deal with real world hardware requirements as well as software limitations.  Due to the massive gameworld and all of the object, NPC's, and PC's that are being interfaced with every single second, zones had to be created to segment the world into different areas and onto different servers so that the hardware could handle the processing for all of this information. 
<br />

<br />
As Tipop points out, the way that Beastlords were implemented from the beginning might not allow this to be easily changed soon or ever. I'll leave that up to the dev's to hash out. Certainly it would be really sweet and more realistic if our pets could zone with us.
<br />

<br />
I never liked the idea that when I zone though some doorway to the next land, my pet goes away. That's just lame...
<br />

<br />
It's great that you can zone and leave mobs behind and clear aggro, but that's about the only good thing about zoning. Me wasting mana to summon and buff a pet or two each time I zone is not good and frankly it's nowhere near realistic to have pets depop when you change zones. I mean is the world suppossed to be fluent or isn't it?
<br />

<br />

<br />
That reminds of last night.  I zoned into an LDoN mission and summoned a pet then stored it fully buffed.  Next, I summoned the second pet and fully buffed it.  As I turned around to begin attacking the mobs at the entrance of the dungeon and clicked on the mob to target it, I was close enough to the zone out that me clicking in mid air to target the mob had actually clicked the zoneout instead. 
<br />

<br />
So...I zoned out on accident, lost both of my fully buffed pets which was 30% of my mana, plus the time that it took to zone. I was really pissed off. Then once I zoned back in I had to blow another 30% mana to full buff 2 more pets.  Not to mention that it was a hard mission and we were pressed to get it done within the time limit which usually poses a challenge. We did end up winning it with 30 minutes left on the timer at least. hehe<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=537728" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://home.pacbell.net/briancc/digsigendo.jpg" border="0" /></a>
<br />
