				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Please pardon my intrusion and length.
<br />

<br />
A good programmer, in my opinion, will never say that something like this "can't be done" or worse "won't be done".  At most, he or she will say that it's going to be hard for these reasons, or even better, counter to the intent and previous design for some other reasons.   I've discussed some of the design issues in the following post:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://forum.magecompendium.com/tower/viewtopic.php?t=9350" target="_blank">http://forum.magecompendium.com/tower/viewtopic.php?t=9350</a>
<br />

<br />
I made that before realizing that this thread existed, and had been already copied here:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://forum.magecompendium.com/tower/viewtopic.php?t=7967" target="_blank">http://forum.magecompendium.com/tower/viewtopic.php?t=7967</a>
<br />

<br />
Going back to the "good programmer" story, often that programmer will honestly say that "it's very difficult and will take a lot of work".   A decent manager can push some more for the feature, explaining the need for it, and often get good results.  What was inconceivable and incredibly difficult can sometimes be often found to be implementable using other techniques when a developer is faced with having to do it the hard way.  By "decent manager" I mean someone who is technically savvy, and can call bluffs and provide new input into implementation and design difficulties (or has access to other people who can play this role.)
<br />

<br />
Customers don't normally play the role of thinking about how something would be implemented, or how difficult it might be in their minds.  Customers have a role in describing facets and level of interest and need in potential features.  Customers in this case should be understood in plural -- none of us gets to decide SOE's development priorities in isolation (if at all...).  The fact that some Beastlords and Mages are both asking for this feature at different times means something.  The fact that some of both are also willing to live without this also means something...
<br />

<br />
The zone-in time in LDoN does bother me.  It's a rare group that asks and waits for inside buffing.  Usually the puller is immediately active (esp. bards, who can't stand still).   Mage buffing also means waiting for pets to be idle, so that "pet toys" can be given to them.  And in some cases, there's already a mob at the zone-in. 
<br />

<br />
But one main reason I'd like this feature would be to put in conjunction with another one -- pets taking group buffs -- so that we could get pets easily buffed like players, and then take them elsewhere.  (Soloing would be an important use case here -- esp. for the casual player, who might not have the time or ability to commit to a group.)  More thought on the buffs can be seen here:  
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://forum.magecompendium.com/tower/viewtopic.php?t=9348" target="_blank">http://forum.magecompendium.com/tower/viewtopic.php?t=9348</a>
<br />

<br />
SOE has recently demonstrated that they are able to extend the character storage significantly -- by the charm slot.  This slot is particularly interesting, as the items it contains are very different, and smart.  It is clearly not inconceivable that they add another slot that would be sufficient to hold a pet (or two... :)  I would also be willing to give up my existing charm for this ability -- e.g. for another charm that grants this ability.  Perhaps I would have the ability to swap charms back and forth -- I could even live with a one-time permanent choice.  In the end, I agree that the information would most likely have to be added to character storage.  The existing complexity and capability of character storage, together with the recent addition of the charm slot, leads me to believe that is not as inconceivable as it might have previously been.
<br />

<br />
There would be good reasons to not allow charmed pets to zone.  They're overpowered to start, and the ability to take a high-level charmed pet to another zone would (a) add additional programming complexity, and (b) add new balance factors, and (c) cause interesting consequences in lowbie zones when charm breaks...
<br />

<br />
To me, the most useful thing that pet class customers can do about this feature is decide on and express their levels of interest.   I agree with the original poster in this thread that the lack of this feature is a liability to the pet classes that no other classes have -- one that slows down certain game play, esp travel and re-login and link death -- that should not be there.  I think that our classes would be more fun to play with this ability.  I think that there would be an effective average power increase with this ability, esp. with the addition of group buffs, but that this power increase is already acheivable with some inconveniece and time.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
